The use of 'sed' command:
-------------------------

-> In Linux, the sed command—short for Stream Editor—is a powerful tool used to filter and transform text. Unlike a traditional text editor (like Notepad or Vim) where you open a file and click around to make changes, sed works non-interactively. 

-> It takes an input stream (a file or output from another command), applies your editing instructions line-by-line, and outputs the result.

-> Syntax:

    # sed 's/<text-to-find>/<replace-text>/' <input-stream>

-> Example:

    # sed 's/Hello/Hi/' info_file.txt    -> Finds the work Hello and replace it with 'Hi' only the first instance found in a line.

*** The output is temporary. Changes are not applied to existing file.

-> How to print the entire file;

    # sed -n 'p' file-name

-> How to print the entire file with line numbers;

    # sed '=' file-name

-> How to print a sentence range;

    # sed -n 'X,Y p' file-name -> prints a specified range

    # sed -n '5,$ p' file-name -> prints from line number 5 upto the last line

    # sed -n '1~5 p' file-name -> prints the first line then prints the line after 5 lines.

-> How to print a partcular line;

    # sed -n '<line-number> p' file-name

-> If you need to replace every instance;

    # sed 's/Hello/Hi/g' info_file.txt -> here the 'g' says global.

*** The command 'sed' will search for the given pattern only, not a specific word.

-> How to replace multiple characters;

    # sed 's/[aB]//g' file-name -> This replaces characters 'a' and 'B' in the file.

-> How to change and write to the file;

    # sed -i 's/Hello/Hi/g' info_file.txt

-> Replace only on lines matching the line pattern:

    # sed '/The/Hello/Hi/' info_file.txt -> find the lines which starts with 'The' word replace pattern 'Hello' with 'Hi'. Only the first instance.

*** To make a global change;

    # sed '/The/Hello/Hi/g' info_file.txt

-> How to delete a pattern:

    # sed '/pattern/d' <file-name> -> Temporary deletion

    # sed -i '/pattern/d' file-name -> changes are appied to the file instantly.

*** # sed '$d' file-name will delete the last line of the file.

-> How to replace multiple patterns with one line of command;

    # sed -e 's/hello/hi/g' -e 's/the/THE/g' file-name

-> How to remove the spaces at the end of lines in a file;

    # sed -i 's/ *$//' file-name

-> How to remove the spaces at the begining of lines in a file;

    # sed -i 's/^ *//' file-name

-> How to remove the tabs at the end of lines in a file;

    # sed -i 's/[[:space:]]*$//' file-name

-> How to remove empty lines:

    # sed -i '/^$/d' file-name

-> How to convert lowercase into uppercase;

    # sed 's/[a-z]/\U&/g' file-name

-> How to convert lowercase into uppercase;

    # sed 's/[A-Z]/\L&/g' file-name

*** # awk 'NR < 10' file-name -> will print the first 10 lines of a file.

-> How to insert a line into a specific location;

    # sed '1i\content' file-name -> insert a new line before the first line of the file



